1 Intro

In this lab, we learn about running regressions, interpreting regression coeffcients, making nice tables, and making coefficient plot.

2 Loading the Data

Let us go back to the old Life Expectancy and urbanization datasets. If you donât have them anymore, you can download them from the following links:

  • Life expectancy data
  • Urbanization data

3 Cleaning the Data

In the next few lines we average life expectancy over country (the original dataset is a panel - with countries and years). This means that we are getting rid of the time component.

#Step1: Calculating the mean
life_expectancy2<-life_expectancy%>%
  group_by(Code, Entity)%>%
  summarize(life_expectancy=mean(Life.expectancy.at.birth..historical., na.rm=T))
#Step2: Cleaning the Data
life_expectancy3<-subset(life_expectancy2, life_expectancy2$Code!="")
#Step1: Calculating the mean
urbanization2<-urbanization%>%
  group_by(Code, Entity)%>%
  summarize(urbanization=mean(Urban.population....of.total.population., na.rm=T))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Code'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.
#Step2: Cleaning the Data
urbanization3<-subset(urbanization2, urbanization2$Code!="")
urbanization3<-subset(urbanization3, select = -c(Entity))

We can now left merge urbanization on life expectancy

#Step1: Performing the left_merge
merged<-left_join(life_expectancy3, urbanization3, by = c("Code" = "Code"))
#Step2: Getting rid of the NAs
merged<-na.omit(merged)
#Step3: Sorting by Entity name
# sort by mpg
merged <- merged[order(merged$Entity),] 
glimpse(merged)

Let us now calculate the correlation between life expectancy and urbanization using the two ways we learned.

4 Correlation between urbanization and life expectancy

As we discussed in the previous lab, we can calculate correlations using the cor command. This is given by the following formula:

\[\rho = \frac{\frac{\Sigma(X_{i} - \bar{X}) (Y_i - \bar{Y})}{n}}{s_X * s_Y}\]

cor_coeff<-cor(merged$life_expectancy,  merged$urbanization, method = c("pearson"))
cor_coeff
[1] 0.6303347

We can use the correlation coefficient to calculate the b.

b_res<-cor_coeff*(sd(merged$life_expectancy)/sd(merged$urbanization))
b_res
[1] 0.2253268

We can also obtain the same result by running a regression

model<-lm(life_expectancy~urbanization, data=merged)
summary(model)

The way we interpret b is the following: every unit increase in urbanization is associated with an increase in life expectancy of 0.225. This effect is highly statistically significant.

5 Creating a regression table

This is how we create a professionally looling table.

model<-lm(life_expectancy~urbanization, data=merged)

models<-list("Life Expectancy" = model)

cm <- c('urbanization'='Urbanization',
        "(Intercept)"="Intercept")

modelsummary(models, stars = TRUE, coef_map = cm, gof_map = c("nobs", "r.squared"))

6 Creating a coefficient plot

We will now use a new function - tidy, which will allow us to save the regression coefficients in a dataframe.

results <- tidy(model)
results

We can plot these coefficients in the following way:

#To calculate the confidence interval, we use 1.96, meaning that 95% of the area under a normal curve lies within approximately 1.96 standard deviations of the mean
ggplot(results, 
       aes(x = estimate, y = term)) +
        geom_point(aes(x = estimate, 
                    y = term))+
  geom_errorbar(aes(xmin = estimate-1.96*std.error, xmax = estimate+1.96*std.error), 
                size = 1, width=0)
Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
â¹ Please use `linewidth` instead.

There is only one issue: the value of the intercept is way too high compared to the value of urbanization. This is why we only see a dot for ubanization and a longer line for the intercept. To fix this problem, we will scale our variables. This means that we substract the mean and divide it by the standard deviation.

model_scaled<-lm(scale(life_expectancy)~scale(urbanization), data=merged)
summary(model_scaled)

Call:
lm(formula = scale(life_expectancy) ~ scale(urbanization), data = merged)

Let us now compare the two models.

model1<-lm(life_expectancy~urbanization, data=merged)
model2<-lm(scale(life_expectancy)~scale(urbanization), data=merged)
models<-list("Unscaled" = model1,
             "Scaled" = model2)

cm <- c('urbanization'='Urbanization',
        'scale(urbanization)' = 'Urbanization',
        "(Intercept)"="Intercept")

modelsummary(models, stars = TRUE, coef_map = cm, gof_map = c("nobs", "r.squared"))

Let us now try to redraw the coefficients.

#Step1: Save the lm results to a dataframe
model2<-lm(scale(life_expectancy)~scale(urbanization), data=merged)
results<-tidy(model2)
#Step2: Plot the results
ggplot(results, 
       aes(x = estimate, y = term)) +
        geom_point(aes(x = estimate, 
                    y = term))+
  geom_errorbar(aes(xmin = estimate-1.96*std.error, xmax = estimate+1.96*std.error), 
                size = 1, width=0)

7 Calculating predicted values and residuals

To calculate the predicted values and residuals, we will simply work with our dataframe.

head(merged, n=10)

We will first add the \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\) to our dataframe.

merged$b<-model1$coefficients["urbanization"]
merged$a<-model1$coefficients[1]
head(merged, n=10)

Let us now compute the predicted values for life expectancy.

merged$y_hat<-merged$b*merged$urbanization + merged$a
head(merged, n=10)

Let us now plot all the y_hats and ys and let us make the y_hats red triangles. In order to do that, we need to split the sample into two and add them on top of each other. We will have the same x. Y will be Y-hat (predicted Y) anad Y (observed Y).

sample1<-subset(merged, select = c(Code, life_expectancy, urbanization))
sample1$type<-"Observed"
head(sample1, n=5)
sample2<-subset(merged, select = c(Code, y_hat, urbanization))
sample2$type<-"Predicted"
names(sample2)[names(sample2)=="y_hat"]<-"life_expectancy"
head(sample2, n=5)

Now we bind the two dataframes by rows.

sample_both<-rbind(sample1, sample2)
# sort by Code
sample_both <- sample_both[order(sample_both$Code),] 
head(sample_both)

Now, we are ready to make the graph.

figure1<-ggplot(sample_both, aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy, 
                                                   color = type, shape=type)) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c('black', "red"))+
  scale_shape_manual(values=c(16, 17))+
  geom_point(size = 3) + 
  geom_segment(aes(x = 0, y = model1$coefficients[1], xend = 100, yend = model1$coefficients[["urbanization"]] * max(merged$urbanization) + model1$coefficients[1]), color = "blue")+
  theme_bw()+
  scale_x_continuous(name = "urbanization", breaks=seq(0,100,20), 
                     limits = c(0,100))+
  scale_y_continuous(name = "life_expectancy", breaks=seq(0,100,20), 
                     limits = c(30,100))+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size=14),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size=14),
        axis.title=element_text(size=14),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        legend.box.background = element_rect(fill='white'),
        legend.background = element_blank(),
        legend.text=element_text(size=12))
figure1

We can now calculate the residuals: residuals are the difference between y_hat and y.

merged$y_resid<-merged$life_expectancy-merged$y_hat

What are the countries that deviate the most from our prediction? Letâs say that we want to emphasize in a scatter plot the 4th quartile countries that deviate the most from our prediction. To do that we go back to our merged dataset. Note that the residuals can be both positive and negative, which is why we take the absolute value.

summary(abs(merged$y_resid))
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
 0.1742  2.2828  4.5135  5.4530  8.2912 18.3322

We can now create a new variables in the dataset that captures whether countries are in that upper quartile deviation.

merged$deviation<-NA
merged$deviation<-"normal"
merged$deviation[abs(merged$y_resid)>8.2912]<-"high"
merged$name_deviation<-NA
merged$name_deviation[abs(merged$y_resid)>8.2912]<-merged$Entity

merged$Entity: number of items to replace is not a multiple of replacement
length
head(merged)
ggplot(merged, aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy, 
                                                   color = deviation, shape=deviation)) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c('red', "black"))+
  scale_shape_manual(values=c(18, 16))+
  geom_point(size = 3) + 
  geom_segment(aes(x = 0, y = model1$coefficients[1], xend = 100, yend = model1$coefficients[["urbanization"]] * max(merged$urbanization) + model1$coefficients[1]), color = "blue")+
  geom_text(aes(label = name_deviation),
              size = 2,

  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size=14),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size=14),
        axis.title=element_text(size=14),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        legend.box.background = element_rect(fill='white'),
        legend.background = element_blank(),
        legend.text=element_text(size=12))

8 Urbanization and life expectancy over time

Up until now, we took the average for both urbanization and life expectancy and we worked very little with the values of these two variables over time.

Let us examine the relationship between life expectancy and urbanization in 1970, 1990, 2000, and 2020

We first go back to our unaveraged datasets. We first clean them.

life_expectancy2<-subset(life_expectancy, life_expectancy$Code!="")
urbanization2<-subset(urbanization, urbanization$Code!="")
#removing entity
names(life_expectancy2)[4]<-"life_expectancy"
names(urbanization2)[4]<-"urbanization"
urbanization2<-subset(urbanization2, select =-c(Entity))

We now join them based on Code and Year

merged_year<-left_join(life_expectancy2, urbanization2, by = c("Code"="Code", "Year"="Year"))

Let us now select the relevant years

merged_1970<-subset(merged_year, Year==1970)
merged_1990<-subset(merged_year, Year==1990)
merged_2000<-subset(merged_year, Year==2000)
merged_2020<-subset(merged_year, Year==2020)

What can we say about the relationship between urbanization and life expectancy over time? It seems that it flattens out. But what if we created more graphs that shows this over time. We can create a gif that allows us to see the evolution of the relationship between urbanization and life expectancy over time.

merged_year_1950on<-subset(merged_year, Year>1950)
figure_animated<-ggplot(merged_year_1950on, mapping = aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point()+
  theme_bw()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(0,100))+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(0,100))+
  labs(title = 'Year: {frame_time}', x = 'urbanization', y = 'life expectancy')+
  transition_states(Year)+
  transition_time(as.integer(Year))

suppressWarnings(animate(figure_animated, height = 600, width =1200, fps = 4,
                         res = 150,
                         nframes=max(merged_year_1950on$Year, na.rm=T)-min(merged_year_1950on$Year, na.rm=T)))
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
